Ah — now I understand exactly where the confusion is: you’re thinking in terms of Rancher-style clusters where the control plane handles everything, and you just deploy pods or workloads. Kuma universal dataplanes are different, and this is why each VM may need a DP:

1️⃣ Why each hub VM needs a DP (universal dataplane)

Kuma “universal DP” ≠ Kubernetes sidecar:

In K8s, Kuma can inject sidecars into pods automatically. The CP talks to all pods via sidecars.

In non-K8s infra (like your Talos OS VMs), there’s no automatic injection — Kuma cannot magically discover services.

A universal DP is an agent that runs on the host machine and registers the service with the global CP.

Effect:

It allows Kuma to do service discovery, mTLS, mesh DNS, traffic routing for services running on plain VMs.

Without a DP, your hub services (runners, APIs) won’t be visible to the mesh and spokes can’t resolve them via Kuma DNS.

Think of it like a “sidecar on the host itself.” It bridges your hub service into the mesh.

2️⃣ You don’t need a DP for every VM if…

All hub services are running on a single VM → one DP can handle multiple services.

The DP configuration allows multiple inbound ports / services.

So it’s not one DP per VM by default — it’s one DP per host or service you want in the mesh.

3️⃣ Example Deployment for Your 5 Talos VM Hub

Let’s assume you have:

5 VMs in your hub (infra)

Services: runner, api, auth

You can do one DP per VM, each DP handling all local services. Here’s an example dataplane YAML for a VM:

type: Dataplane
mesh: infra
name: hub-vm1
networking:
  address: 10.0.0.1  # VM IP
  inbound:
    - port: 8080
      servicePort: 8080
      tags:
        service: runner
    - port: 9090
      servicePort: 9090
      tags:
        service: api
    - port: 7070
      servicePort: 7070
      tags:
        service: auth
  outbound:
    - port: 5681
      service: "*"

Then on the VM, run:

kuma-dp run --cp-address=http://<global-cp-ip>:5681 --dataplane-file=hub-vm1.yaml

Repeat for each VM (hub-vm2.yaml, hub-vm3.yaml, etc.) with their respective IPs.

All inbound services are now visible to spokes via service.mesh DNS.

✅ Key Advantages

No extra cluster needed — just use existing hub VMs.

Unified mesh — global CP sees all hub and spoke DPs.

Works with services on plain VMs — no Kubernetes required.

